        </task>

      </activity>
    </worksheet>

    <p>
      The next activity gives you an opportunity to practice the algebraic
      aspects of solving a constrained optimization problem using the method of
      Lagrange multipliers.
    </p>

    <worksheet>
      <activity workspace="1.5in" xml:id="A_mv_deriv-lagrange_1">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            A cylindrical soda can holds about 355 cc of liquid.
            In this activity, we want to find the dimensions of such a can that
            will minimize the surface area.
            For the sake of simplicity, assume the can is a perfect cylinder.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What are the variables in this problem?
              Based on the context, what restriction(s), if any, are there on
              these variables?
            </p>
          </statement>

          <answer>
            <p>
              Let <m>r</m> by the radius and <m>h</m> the height of the can.
              We need <m>r \gt 0</m>, <m>h\gt 0</m>, and
              <m>V=\pi r^2 h = 355</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Assume the can is cylindrical.
              Let <m>r</m> by the radius and <m>h</m> the height of the can.
              The volume <m>V</m> of the can is constant at 355 cc of liquid.
              The radius and height can be any positive numbers as long as the
              volume is 355: <m>V=\pi r^2 h = 355</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What quantity do we want to optimize in this problem?
              What equation describes the constraint?
              (You need to decide which of these functions plays the role of
              <m>f</m> and which plays the role of <m>g</m> in our discussion of
              Lagrange multipliers.)
            </p>
          </statement>

          <answer>
            <p>
              Minimize surface area
              <m>
            A(r,h) = 2\pi r^2 + 2\pi r h
          </m>
              subject to <m>
            V(r,h) = \pi r^2 h= 355
          </m>.
            </p>
          </answer>

          <solution>
            <p>
              We want to minimize the surface area <m>A</m> of the can, where
              <m>
            A(r,h) = 2\pi r^2 + 2\pi r h
          </m>.
              The volume of the can is <m>V(r,h) = \pi r^2 h</m>, so our
              constraint is
              <m>
            V(r,h) = \pi r^2 h = 355
          </m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find <m>\lambda</m> and the values of your variables that satisfy
              Equation <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-parallel"/> in the
              context of this problem.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>
            r \approx 3.84 \text{ cm }
          </m>,
              <m>
            h = \frac{355}{\pi r^2} \approx 7.66 \text{ cm }
          </m>,
              <m>
            \lambda = \frac{2}{r} \approx 0.52
          </m>.
            </p>
          </answer>

          <solution>
            <p>
              To solve this constrained optimization problem, we need to find
              the values of <m>\lambda</m>, <m>r</m>, and <m>h</m> that satisfy
              <md>
                <mrow>\nabla A \amp = \lambda \nabla V</mrow>
                <mrow>\left\langle 4\pi r + 2\pi h, 2 \pi r \right\rangle \amp = \lambda \left\langle 2\pi rh, \pi r^2 \right\rangle</mrow>
              </md>.
              So we have to solve the equations
              <md>
                <mrow>\pi r^2h \amp = 355</mrow>
                <mrow>4\pi r + 2\pi h \amp = \lambda 2\pi rh</mrow>
                <mrow>2 \pi r \amp = \lambda \pi r^2</mrow>
              </md>.
              Since <m>r \gt 0</m>, these equations simplify to
              <md>
                <mrow>2\pi r^2h \amp = 355</mrow>
                <mrow>2r + h \amp = \lambda rh</mrow>
                <mrow>2 \amp = \lambda r</mrow>
              </md>.
              So
              <md number="yes" xml:id="eq_LM_example1">
                \lambda = \frac{2}{r} = \frac{2r+h}{rh}
              </md>.
              Now
              <md>
                h = \frac{355}{\pi r^2}
              </md>,
              so equation <xref ref="eq_LM_example1"/> becomes
              <md>
                \frac{2}{r} = \frac{r+h}{rh} = \frac{2\pi r^3+355}{355r}
              </md>.
              Applying some algebra yields
              <md>
                <mrow>\frac{2}{r} \amp = \frac{2\pi r^3+355}{355r}</mrow>
                <mrow>710 \amp = 2\pi r^3 + 355</mrow>
                <mrow>r^3 \amp = \frac{355}{2\pi}</mrow>
                <mrow>r \amp = \sqrt[3]{\frac{355}{2\pi}}</mrow>
                <mrow>r \amp \approx 3.84 \text{ cm } </mrow>
              </md>.
              This makes
              <md>
                h = \frac{355}{\pi r^2} \approx 7.66 \text{ cm }
              </md>
              and
              <md>
                \lambda = \frac{2}{r} \approx 0.52
              </md>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Determine the dimensions of the soda can that give the desired
              solution to this constrained optimization problem.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>
            r \approx 3.84 \text{ cm }
          </m>,
              <m>
            h = \frac{355}{\pi r^2} \approx 7.66 \text{ cm }
          </m>
            </p>
          </answer>

          <solution>
            <p>
              To minimize the surface area under the assumptions we have made,
              the radius should be approximately 3.84 cm and the height
              approximately 7.66 cm.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </activity>
    </worksheet>

    <p>
      The method of Lagrange multipliers also works for functions of three
      variables.
      That is, if we have a function <m>f = f(x,y,z)</m> that we want to
      optimize subject to a constraint <m>g(x,y,z) = c</m>, the optimal point
      <m>(x,y,z)</m> lies on the level surface <m>S</m> defined by the
      constraint <m>g(x,y,z) = k</m>.
      Because gradient vectors are orthogonal to level <em>surfaces</em> as well, the argument we made to justify the need for the gradient of the objective function to be parallel to the gradient of the constraint at the location of an exreme value still holds.
      In other words, just as in the two variable case, we can optimize <m>f(x,y,z)</m>
      subject to the constraint <m>g(x,y,z) = c</m> by finding all points
      <m>(x,y,z)</m> that satisfy <m>\nabla f = \lambda \nabla g</m> and
      <m>g(x,y,z) = c</m>. (In fact, this method also works for functions of an arbitrary number of variables.)
    </p>
    <p>
      The following example illustrates using the method of Lagrange multipliers to optimize a function of three variables. While the problem in the previous activity is one that you could have solved using only single-variable calculus techniques such as solving the constraint equation for one variable and substituting into the objective function to reduce the number of variables, this example also illustrates how Lagrange multipliers can be used to help solve problems that are not amenable to that strategy.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Suppose that we have created a three-dimensional coordinate system for a heated chamber with the origin at the center of the chamber. The temperature, in degrees Celsius, at the point <m>(x,y,z)</m> inside the chamber is given by <m>T(x,y,z) = 6x-3y^2+8z+400</m>. We wish to find the hottest and coldest points on the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2 = 100</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        To fit our usual framework of a Lagrange multipliers problem, let <m>g(x,y,z) = x^2+y^2+z^2</m>. Our goal here then becomes to optimize <m>T</m> subject to the constraint <m>g(x,y,z)=100</m>. We begin by computing the gradients:
        <md>
          <mrow>\nabla T \amp = \langle 6, -3y, 8\rangle</mrow>
          <mrow>\nabla g \amp = \langle 2x, 2y, 2z\rangle</mrow>
        </md>
        Since the method of Lagrange multipliers tells us that the extreme values will occur where the gradients are parallel, we need <m>\nabla T = \lambda \nabla g</m> as well as <m>g(x,y,z)=100</m>. This leads to the following equations:
        <md number="yes">
          <mrow xml:id="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-x">6 \amp = 2\lambda x</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-y">-6y \amp = 2\lambda y</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-z">8 \amp = 2\lambda z</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-constraint">x^2+y^2+z^2 \amp = 100</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        The second equation can be rewritten as <md>0= 2\lambda y +6y = 2y(\lambda + 3)</md>. Thus, we know that solutions of the system must have <m>y=0</m> or <m>\lambda = -3</m>. We consider each of these cases separately:
        <dl width="narrow">
          <li>
            <title><m>y=0</m></title>
            <p>
              In this case, we first isolate <m>x</m> and <m>z</m> in <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-x"/> and <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-z"/>, respectively. We then substitute <m>x=3/\lambda</m>, <m>y=0</m>, and <m>z=4/\lambda</m> into <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-constraint"/>, which gives us
              <md>
                <mrow>\left(\frac{3}{\lambda}\right)^2 + 0^2 + \left(\frac{4}{\lambda}\right)^2 \amp= 100</mrow>
                <mrow>9 + 16 \amp= 100\lambda^2</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{1}{4} \amp = \lambda^2</mrow>
                <mrow>\pm\frac{1}{2} \amp = \lambda</mrow>
              </md>.
              We can now substitute the values of <m>\lambda</m> into <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-x"/> and <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-z"/>. This gives us two points: <m>(6,0,8)</m> and <m>(-6, 0, -8)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title><m>\lambda = -3</m></title>
            <p>
              By using <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-x"/> and <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-z"/>, this leads us to find directly that <m>x=-1</m> and <m>z=-4/3</m>. Now we can substitute into <xref ref="eqn-mv_deriv-lagrange-temp-constraint"/> and solve for <m>y</m>, which gives <m>y=\pm 5\sqrt{35}/3</m>. Therefore, we have two points to consider: <m>(-1,5\sqrt{35}/3, -4/3)</m> and <m>(-1, -5\sqrt{35}/3, -4/3)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
      <p>
        Now that we have found the four potential locations of our extreme values, we need so evaluate <m>T</m> at each of these points. The points and the temperature values are shown below.
      </p>
      <tabular>
        <col right="minor"/><col/>
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell><m>(x,y,z)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>T(x,y,z)</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(6,0,8)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>500</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(-6,0,-8)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>300</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(-1,5\sqrt{35}/3,-4/3)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>275/3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(-1,-5\sqrt{35}/3,-4/3)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>275/3</m></cell>
        </row>        
      </tabular>
      <p>
        Therefore, we can see that the minimum temperature of a point on the sphere is <m>275/3\approx 91.67^\circ\text{C}</m>, which occurs at the points <m>(-1,5\sqrt{35}/3,-4/3)</m> and <m>(-1,-5\sqrt{35}/3,-4/3)</m>. The maximum temperature of a point on the sphere is <m>500^\circ\text{C}</m>, which occurs at the point <m>(6,0,8)</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      If it has not yet become apparent to you, solving the system of equations is generally the most difficult part of using the method of Lagrange multipliers. In most cases, this system is <em>nonlinear</em>, meaning that at least one variable will appear to a power other than 1 or variables are multiplied (or perhaps trigonometric, exponential, or logarithmic functions appear). We cannot provide a general method that will work to solve every nonlinear system of equations, so you may need to experiment a bit to find a the solutions. The final activity of this section gives you an opportunity to practice this for another function of three variables.
    </p>
    <worksheet>
      <activity workspace="1.5in" xml:id="A_mv_deriv-lagrange_2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the method of Lagrange multipliers to find the dimensions of the
            least expensive rectangular packing crate with a volume of 240 cubic feet when
            the material for the top costs $2 per square foot, the bottom costs $3
            per square foot, and the sides cost $1.50 per square foot.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>5.24 \times 5.24 \times 8.74</m> feet.
          </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <p>
            We want to minimize the cost <m>C</m> of the crate.
            Let <m>x</m> be the length, <m>y</m> the width, and <m>z</m> the
            height of the crate.
            The volume <m>V = xyz</m> of the crate is to be 240 cubic feet, so
            <m>x \gt 0</m>, <m>y \gt 0</m>, and <m>z \gt 0</m>.
            The area of the top and bottom of the crate is <m>2xy</m>, so the
            cost of the top of the crate is <m>2xy</m> and the cost of the
            bottom is <m>3xy</m>.
            The area of the sides of the crate is <m>2xz + 2yz</m> and so the
            cost of the sides is <m>1.5(2xz+2yz)</m>.
            Thus, the total cost of the crate is
            <md>
              C(x,y,z) = 5xy + 3(xz+yz)
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            The volume of the crate is to be 240 cubic feet, so our constraint
            is
            <md>
              240 = V(x,y,z) = xyz
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Now
            <md>
              \nabla C = \lambda \nabla V
            </md>
            implies
            <md>
              \nabla C = \langle 5y+3z, 5x+3z, 3(x+y) \rangle = \lambda \langle yz, xz, xy \rangle
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            So we need to solve the system of equations
            <md>
              <mrow>xyz \amp = 240</mrow>
              <mrow>5y+3z \amp = \lambda(yz)</mrow>
              <mrow>5x+3z \amp = \lambda(xz)</mrow>
              <mrow>3(x+y) \amp = \lambda(xy)</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            The last three equations give us
            <md>
              \lambda = \frac{5}{z} + \frac{3}{y} = \frac{5}{z}+\frac{3}{x} = \frac{3}{x}+\frac{3}{y}
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Using the fact that <m>z = \frac{240}{xy}</m> we have
            <md>
              \frac{xy}{48}+\frac{3}{y} = \frac{xy}{248}+\frac{3}{x} = \frac{3}{y}+\frac{3}{x}
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Using the equation
            <md>
              \frac{xy}{48}+\frac{3}{y} =  \frac{3}{y}+\frac{3}{x}
            </md>
            gives us
            <md>
              y = \frac{144}{x^2}
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Then we substitute into the equation
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{xy}{48}+\frac{3}{x} \amp = \frac{3}{y}+\frac{3}{x}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{xy}{48} \amp = \frac{3}{y}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{3}{x} \amp = \frac{x^2}{48}</mrow>
              <mrow>x^3 \amp = 144</mrow>
              <mrow>x \amp = \sqrt[3]{144}</mrow>
              <mrow>x \amp \approx 5.24 \text{ ft } </mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Then
            <md>
              y = \frac{144}{x^2} = \sqrt[3]{144} \approx 5.24 \text{ ft }
            </md>
            and
            <md>
              z = \frac{240}{xy} = \approx 8.74 \text{ ft }
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Also,
            <md>
              \lambda = \frac{3}{x}+\frac{3}{y} \approx 1.15
            </md>.
          </p>

          <p>
            So to minimize the cost of this crate, the crate should be a box of
            approximate dimensions <m>5.24 \times 5.24 \times 8.74</m> feet.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>
    </worksheet>


  </subsection>

  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The extrema of a function <m>f=f(x,y)</m> subject to a constraint
          <m>g(x,y) = c</m> occur at points for which the contour of <m>f</m> is
          tangent to the curve that represents the constraint equation.
          This occurs when
          <md>
            \nabla f = \lambda \nabla g.
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          We use the condition <m>\nabla f = \lambda \nabla g</m> to generate a
          system of equations, together with the constraint <m>g(x,y) = c</m>,
          that may be solved for <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>\lambda</m>.
          Once we have all the solutions, we evaluate <m>f</m> at each of the
          <m>(x,y)</m> points to determine the extrema.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </outcomes>
